recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Perched on chain link fence. 

# Habitat #
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

# Editing #
Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, cutoff 2 khz, order 3

# Equipment #
Fostex FR-2 digital field recorder with Telinga Pro 22" parabolic reflector

recordings.rmk: This recording was not modified. I observed the bird only briefly visually, with enough time to write down key identifying characteristics like its reddish cap and the line through its eye. It was hopping in and around some shrubbery. This Chipping Sparrow was observed in an open grassland environment, with the largest plants being coyote brush and the occasional coast live oak. Notably, however, the meadow is close to both a developed area of campus (the recital hall and nearby areas) and a more typical forest, with coast redwood, tanoak, etc. I do not know the bird's sex. Lighting conditions were good, though approaching dusk.

recordings.loc: Midville Branch, Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia
Midville Branch, Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia
recordings.rmk:
My first reaction to hearing this song was that it didn't sound like the Dark-eyed Junco, and if a Chipping Sparrow, it sounded unusual, more dry. Did not see the bird in question, obviously. So it's a mystery.

The song moved around, and bird sang from several areas, repeating the circuit several times...singing from mid-story, not the tree tops...seeming to come at times from maybe 8-10 ft off the ground only. 

Compared this sonogram with the recordings here for Spizella passerina, and found a few which were comparable, though most were at a more expanded range than my recording here. The compression in my recording makes it sound somewhat like Helmitheros vermivorum in range (4-7 kHz)...and this compression gives it a "drier" sound than seems to be typically found with Spizella passerina?

(I'm putting it down as Spizella passerina, as I was able to spot one at the same location a few days later).

recordings.loc: Midville Branch, Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia
recordings.rmk:
Coming from edge of field and woods (mixed pine, hemlock, maple, oak, ash, with young trees at edge and mature trees within.

recordings.loc: Relative's yard, Briarcliff Manor, New York
recordings.rmk: Habitat: suburban backyard. Ordinarily I'd assume this was a Chipping Sparrow, but there seems to be a problem. Every other Chipping Sparrow I've heard, whether in person or in recordings, has has repeated a monosyllabic note as its trill. When I slowed this one down, it seemed to be alternating between two syllables. This yard is fine for Chipping Sparrow,  but I don't think this is where you'd find a singing Swamp Sparrow, which is what this reminds me of. Any ideas? Or if this is a Chipping Sparrow on why this might be singing the way it is?
